  "prompt": "Japanese Etiquette, Behavior, and Habits: How does tipping work in Japan?",
  "response": "In Japan, tipping is not a common practice and can actually be considered rude or confusing. The Japanese culture places a high value on providing excellent service as part of one's professional duties, and the cost of service is typically included in the bill. Here are some key points regarding tipping in Japan:\n\n1. **Restaurants and Cafes**: When dining out, you do not need to leave a tip. The bill you receive will include all charges, and you simply pay the amount shown.\n\n2. **Hotels**: Tipping is generally not expected in hotels. However, some high-end hotels may have a practice of giving a small gratuity to the staff who directly assist you, such as a bellhop. In such cases, it is done discreetly, often by placing money in an envelope.\n\n3. **Taxis**: Taxi drivers in Japan do not expect tips. You simply pay the fare as indicated by the meter.\n\n4. **Spas and Salons**: Similar to other service industries, tipping is not expected at spas and salons.\n\n5. **Tours and Guides**: While tipping tour guides is not typical, if you feel your guide has provided exceptional service, you could express your gratitude in other ways, such as a small gift or a polite thank-you note.\n\nOverall, tipping is not part of Japanese culture, and providing excellent service is seen as a standard part of doing one's job. If you do wish to show appreciation, a sincere thank-you or a small, thoughtful gift is more appropriate than monetary tips.",
